Networking Basics: Ports and Standard Ports

1. Ports in Networking

Ports are logical points where data is exchanged between devices.

A device connects to a specific port to communicate with a service.

Ports act like a harbour for ships, where data enters and leaves a system.

Ports control which applications or services can communicate over the network.

Once a connection is established, all data transmission occurs through ports.

Ports are numerical identifiers ranging from 0 to 65,535.



2. Why Standard Ports Are Used

Since there are 65,535 ports, it can be difficult to identify which application uses which port.

To solve this problem, standard rules assign specific ports to specific protocols.

This ensures consistency and compatibility across different systems and applications.

Example:

Web browser traffic typically uses Port 80.

Because of this standard, all browsers follow the same rule when accessing web pages.



3. Common Ports

Ports between 0 and 1023 are known as Common Ports (or Well-Known Ports).

These ports are reserved for standard protocols and important services.



4. Important Ports and Protocols

FTP (File Transfer Protocol)

Port: 21

Used for file transfer between systems.

Allows uploading and downloading files from a central server.


SSH (Secure Shell)

Port: 22

Used for secure remote login into systems.

Works through a text-based command-line interface.


HTTP (HyperText Transfer Protocol)

Port: 80

Used to access websites and transfer web content.

Transfers data such as text, images, and videos.


HTTPS (HyperText Transfer Protocol Secure)

Port: 443

Secure version of HTTP.

Uses encryption to protect data during transmission.


SMB (Server Message Block)

Port: 445

Used for file sharing and sharing devices such as printers on a network.


RDP (Remote Desktop Protocol)

Port: 3389

Used to remotely access and control another computer using a graphical interface.



5. Important Note

Protocols usually follow standard port numbers, but applications can run on different ports if configured.

